# Use `useGuardedRouter` for programmatic navigation

When a component calls `router.push()` or `router.replace()` programmatically (i.e. in a click handler, effect, or callback — **not** via a `<Link>` tag), use `useGuardedRouter` from `@/lib/navigation/useGuardedRouter` instead of `useRouter`.

`useGuardedRouter` is a drop-in replacement. It automatically shows the transcribe leave-guard confirmation modal when the user is on `/transcribe` with pending work (recording, uploading, or transcribing in flight). On any other route it is a no-op pass-through.

```typescript
// ❌ WRONG — router.push bypasses the leave guard on /transcribe
import { useRouter } from 'next/navigation';
const router = useRouter();
router.push('/m/some-uuid');

// ✅ CORRECT — leave guard fires automatically when needed
import { useGuardedRouter } from '@/lib/navigation/useGuardedRouter';
const router = useGuardedRouter();
router.push('/m/some-uuid');
```

## When this applies

- Any component that calls `router.push()` or `router.replace()` inside a click handler, effect, or async callback.

## When this does NOT apply

- `<Link href="...">` — the leave guard intercepts those at the DOM level already.
- `router.back()`, `router.forward()`, `router.refresh()`, `router.prefetch()` — these are passed through unchanged and do not need guarding.
